This module adopts the same governance shape as terraform-aws-vpc,
terraform-aws-iam, terraform-aws-s3, and terraform-aws-kms: unified
Foundation Plan §15.2 tagging, the central reusable CI workflow in
devotica-labs/terraform-shared-config, and conftest policies from
devotica-labs/terraform-policies.

Defaults are aligned with fintech compliance requirements:

- Storage encryption forced on; caller must supply a KMS key ARN (no
  plaintext RDS — RBI / DPDP / PCI / SOC 2).
- Deletion protection on by default (the cost of accidental deletion
  >>> the friction of toggling this off before a planned teardown).
- Multi-AZ on by default (losing the primary mid-transaction without
  failover is the worst-case scenario in fintech).
- IAM database authentication on by default (passwordless access via
  IAM principals — pairs with terraform-aws-iam).
- Modern AWS-managed master password by default (manage_master_user_password
  = true): RDS creates the secret in AWS Secrets Manager with automatic
  rotation. Caller never sees the plaintext.
- Performance Insights on by default (7-day free retention).
- Backup retention floor of 7 days (RBI / SEBI minimum); module accepts
  up to 35 (the AWS maximum).
- publicly_accessible = true is validated and refused.

Single-instance non-Aurora is the only shape supported in v0.1. Aurora
clusters belong in a sister module (terraform-aws-rds-aurora) — single-
instance Aurora is an antipattern.

